# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boost-cpp-lib
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] The **Boost C++ Libraries** (also known simply as **Boost**) are a set of libraries for the C++ programming language that provides support for tasks and structures such as linear algebra, pseudorandom number generation, multithreading, image processing, regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] It currently contains 170 individual libraries.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] All of the Boost libraries are licensed under the Boost Software License, designed to allow Boost to be used with both free and proprietary software projects.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Boost is used complementary with the C++ Standard Library to supplement its features.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] The Boost community emerged around 1998, when the first version of the standard was released.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] It has grown continuously since then and now plays a big role in the standardization of C++.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Even though there is no formal relationship between the Boost community and the standardization committee, some of the developers are active in both groups.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] The libraries are aimed at a wide range of C++ users and application domains.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] In order to ensure efficiency and flexibility, Boost makes extensive use of templates.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Boost has been a source of extensive work and research into generic programming and metaprogramming in C++.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Most Boost libraries are header based, consisting of inline functions and templates, and as such do not need to be built in advance of their use.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Some Boost libraries coexist as independent libraries.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Some Boost libraries, such as `boost.regex`, are offered as modules, as the rest of the library begins to support modules.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Boost was founded in 1998 by three members of the C++ Standards Committee: Beman Dawes, David Abrahams, and Robert Klarer.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] The idea originated during a conversation between Klarer and Dawes at the March 1998 C++ Standards Committee meeting in Sophia Antipolis, France, with Abrahams joining shortly thereafter to establish the first Boost mailing list.*"History of Boost".
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Retrieved 26 January 2026.**Stroustrup, Bjarne; Sutter, Herb (1 December 2020).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Beman Dawes (died December 2020) served on the C++ Standards Committee (WG21) from 1992 and chaired the Library Working Group for five years during the completion of C++98.*Stroustrup, Bjarne; Sutter, Herb (1 December 2020).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Retrieved 26 January 2026.* He was the original author of the Boost.Filesystem library, which later formed the basis for the std::filesystem library in C++17.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Dawes was instrumental in establishing Boost's peer-review process and testing culture.*"History of Boost".
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] David Abrahams was a member of the C++ Standards Committee from 1996 to 2012 and is known for developing the theory of exception safety for C++, including the "Abrahams guarantees" framework.*"David Abrahams (computer programmer)".
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Retrieved 26 January 2026.* He authored multiple Boost libraries including Boost.Python and co-authored the book *C++ Template Metaprogramming* (2004).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] In 2001, Abrahams founded Boost Consulting (later BoostPro Computing) to provide commercial support for Boost libraries.*"David Abrahams (computer programmer)".
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Robert Klarer, working at IBM, co-initiated the Boost concept with Dawes and contributed to early discussions on best practices for high-quality library development.*"History of Boost".
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Retrieved 26 January 2026.* There are mailing lists devoted to Boost library use and library development, active as of 2023.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] Boost is licensed under its own free, open-source license, known as the Boost Software License.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] It is a permissive license in the style of the BSD license and the MIT license, but without requiring attribution for redistribution in binary form.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/boost-c-libraries] The license has been OSI-approved since February 2008 and is considered a free software license, compatible with the GNU General Public License, by the Free Software Foundation.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] In the C++ programming language, the **C++ Standard Library** is a collection of classes and functions, which are written in the core language and part of the C++ ISO Standard itself.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The C++ Standard Library also incorporates most headers of the ISO C standard library ending with ".h", but their use was deprecated (reverted the deprecation since C++23).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] C++23 instead considers these headers as useful for interoperability with C, and recommends against their usage outside of programs that are intended to be both valid C and C++ programs.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] No other headers in the C++ Standard Library end in ".h".
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] Features of the C++ Standard Library are declared within the `std` namespace.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The C++ Standard Library is based upon conventions introduced by the Standard Template Library (STL), and has been influenced by research in generic programming and developers of the STL such as Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] Although the C++ Standard Library and the STL share many features, neither is a strict superset of the other.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The design of the C++ standard library, much like the C standard library, is minimalistic, and contains only core features for programming, lacking most of the more specialised features offered by the Java standard library or C# standard library.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] For more features, some third-party libraries such as Boost libraries and POCO C++ Libraries, which offer additional features, may be used to supplement the standard library.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] An implementation for a C++ standard library header is described as "freestanding" if the execution of the program does not rely on an operating system.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] A noteworthy feature of the C++ Standard Library is that it not only specifies the syntax and semantics of generic algorithms, but also places requirements on their performance.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] These performance requirements often correspond to a well-known algorithm, which is expected but not required to be used.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] In most cases this requires linear time O(*n*) or linearithmic time O(*n* log *n*), but in some cases higher bounds are allowed, such as quasilinear time O(*n* log2 *n*) for stable sort (to allow in-place merge sort).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] In other cases requirements remain laxer, such as selection, which is only required to be linear on average (as in quickselect), not requiring worst-case linear as in introselect.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The C++ Standard Library underwent ISO standardization as part of the C++ ISO Standardization effort in the 1990s.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] Since 2011, it has been expanded and updated every three years with each revision of the C++ standard.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] C++20 specifies the introduction of standard library header units, and C++23 adds full module support for the standard library.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] The Apache C++ Standard Library is another open-source implementation.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] It was originally developed commercially by Rogue Wave Software and later donated to the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c-standard-library] However, after more than five years without a release, the board of the Apache Software Foundation decided to end this project and move it to Apache Attic.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] C++ was designed with systems programming and embedded, resource-constrained software and large systems in mind, with performance, efficiency, and flexibility of use as its design highlights.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), with the latest standard version ratified and published by ISO in October 2024 as *ISO/IEC 14882:2024* (informally known as C++23).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The C++ programming language was initially standardized in 1998 as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which was then amended by the C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17, and C++20 standards.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The next C++23 standard superseded these with new features and an enlarged standard library.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Before the initial standardization in 1998, C++ was developed by Stroustrup at Bell Labs since 1979 as an extension of the C language; he wanted an efficient and flexible language similar to C that also provided high-level features for program organization.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Since 2012, C++ has been on a three-year release schedule with C++29 as the next planned standard.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In 1979, Bjarne Stroustrup, a Danish computer scientist, began work on "C with Classes", the predecessor to C++.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The motivation for creating a new language originated from Stroustrup's experience in programming for his PhD thesis.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup found that Simula had features that were very helpful for large software development, but the language was too slow for practical use, while BCPL was fast but too low-level to be suitable for large software development.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] When Stroustrup started working in AT&T Bell Labs, he had the problem of analyzing the UNIX kernel with respect to distributed computing.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Remembering his PhD experience, Stroustrup set out to enhance the C language with Simula-like features.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] C was chosen because it was general-purpose, fast, portable, and widely used.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In addition to C and Simula's influences, other languages influenced this new language, including ALGOL 68, Ada, CLU, and ML.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Initially, Stroustrup's "C with Classes" added features to the C compiler, Cpre, including classes, derived classes, strong typing, inlining, and default arguments.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In 1982, Stroustrup began designing a cleaned-up and extended successor to C with Classes, using traditional compiler technology.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The language was briefly called C84 before the name C++ was adopted; the name was suggested by Rick Mascitti and refers to C's `++` increment operator.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The resulting language included virtual functions, function and operator overloading, references, `const`, improved type checking, user-controlled free-store memory allocation (`new`/`delete`), and BCPL-style single-line `//` comments.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup also designed and implemented Cfront, the C++ compiler front end, between spring 1982 and summer 1983.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In 1984, Stroustrup implemented the first stream input/output library.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The idea of providing an output operator rather than a named output function was suggested by Doug McIlroy (who had previously suggested Unix pipes).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In 1985, the first edition of *The C++ Programming Language* was released, which became the definitive reference for the language, as there was not yet an official standard.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The first commercial implementation of C++ was released in October of the same year.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In 1989, C++ 2.0 was released, followed by the updated second edition of *The C++ Programming Language* in 1991.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] New features in 2.0 included multiple inheritance, abstract classes, static member functions, const member functions, and protected members.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In 1990, *The Annotated C++ Reference Manual* was published.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] This work became the basis for the future standard.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Later feature additions included templates, exceptions, namespaces, new casts, and a Boolean type.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, C++98 was released, standardizing the language, and a minor update (C++03) was released in 2003.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] After C++98, C++ evolved relatively slowly until, in 2011, the C++11 standard was released, adding numerous new features, enlarging the standard library further, and providing more facilities to C++ programmers.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] After a minor C++14 update released in December 2014, various new additions were introduced in C++17.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] After becoming finalized in February 2020, a draft of the C++20 standard was approved on 4 September 2020, and officially published on 15 December 2020.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] On January 3, 2018, Stroustrup was announced as the 2018 winner of the Charles Stark Draper Prize for Engineering, "for conceptualizing and developing the C++ programming language".
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In December 2022, C++ ranked third on the TIOBE index, surpassing Java for the first time in the history of the index.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] As of November 2024, the language ranks second after Python, with Java being in third.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In March 2025, Stroustrup issued a call for the language community to defend it.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Since the language allows manual memory management, bugs that represent security risks such as buffer overflow may be introduced in programs when inadvertently misused by the programmer.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] According to Stroustrup, "the name signifies the evolutionary nature of the changes from C." This name is credited to Rick Mascitti (mid-1983) and was first used in December 1983.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] When Mascitti was questioned informally in 1992 about the naming, he indicated that it was given in a tongue-in-cheek spirit.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The name comes from C's `++` operator (which increments the value of a variable) and a common naming convention of using "+" to indicate an enhanced computer program.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] During C++'s development period, the language had been referred to as "new C" and "C with Classes" before acquiring its final name.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by an ISO working group known as JTC1/SC22/WG21.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The working group holds three week-long meetings each year.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] So far, it has published seven revisions of the C++ standard and is currently working on the next revision, C++26.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, the ISO working group standardized C++ for the first time as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which is informally known as *C++98*.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In 2003, it published a new version of the C++ standard called *ISO/IEC 14882:2003*, which fixed problems identified in C++98.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The next major revision of the standard was informally referred to as "C++0x", but it was not released until 2011.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] C++11 (14882:2011) included many additions to both the core language and the standard library.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] In 2014, C++14 (also known as C++1y) was released as a small extension to C++11, featuring mainly bug fixes and small improvements.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The Draft International Standard ballot procedures completed in mid-August 2014.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] After C++14, a major revision C++17, informally known as C++1z, was completed by the ISO C++ committee in mid July 2017 and was approved and published in December 2017.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The C++ language has two main components: a direct mapping of hardware features provided primarily by the C subset, and zero-overhead abstractions based on those mappings.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup describes C++ as "a light-weight abstraction programming language [designed] for building and using efficient and elegant abstractions"; and "offering both hardware access and abstraction is the basis of C++.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] A hello world program that conforms to the C standard is also a valid C++ hello world program.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The C++ standard specifies both the core language and the standard library.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The library clauses describe the contents of the library, how a well-formed C++ program uses it, and the requirements placed on conforming implementations.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The standard library is organized into areas such as language support, diagnostics, memory management, metaprogramming, general utilities, containers, iterators, ranges, algorithms, strings, text processing, numerics, time, input/output, and concurrency support.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] It also provides the facilities of the C standard library through C++ headers such as `<cstdio>` and `<cstdlib>`; except for names defined as macros in C, these declarations are placed in namespace `std`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Library facilities are traditionally made available by including standard headers, for example `#include <vector>`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Since C++20, importable standard library headers may also be imported as header units.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] C++23 added the named standard library modules `std` and `std.compat`: `std` exports declarations in namespace `std`, while `std.compat` also exports corresponding global namespace declarations for C library facilities.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] A major influence on the standard library was the Standard Template Library (STL), a generic programming library proposed to the C++ standards committee by Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee in 1994.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Its model of containers, iterators, and generic algorithms became part of the Standard C++ Library, although the standard library also includes many other facilities, such as input/output, localization, diagnostics, and the C library subset.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The main aim is to efficiently and consistently write type and resource safe C++.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Despite this, the guidelines are not endorsed by the ISO C++ standards committee and do not represent the consensus of the committee.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The Core Guidelines were announced in the opening keynote at CPPCon 2015.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The Guidelines are accompanied by the Guideline Support Library (GSL), a header-only library of types and functions to implement the Core Guidelines and static checker tools for enforcing Guideline rules.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] One of the largest implementations of this is Microsoft's implementation.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Many of the existing features in the GSL have been later integrated into the language, such as `std::byte`, smart pointers, and `std::span`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] To give compiler vendors greater freedom, the C++ standards committee decided not to dictate the implementation of name mangling, exception handling, and other implementation-specific features.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] The downside of this decision is that object code produced by different compilers is expected to be incompatible.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] There are, however, attempts to standardize compilers for particular machines or operating systems.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] For example, the Itanium C++ ABI is processor-independent (despite its name) and is implemented by GCC and Clang.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] C++ is often considered to be a superset of C but this is not strictly true.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Most C code can easily be made to compile correctly in C++ but there are a few differences that cause some valid C code to be invalid or behave differently in C++.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] For example, C allows implicit conversion from `void*` to other pointer types but C++ does not (for type safety reasons).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Also, C++ defines many new keywords, such as `new` and `class`, which may be used as identifiers (for example, variable names) in a C program.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Some incompatibilities have been removed by the 1999 revision of the C standard (C99), which now supports C++ features such as line comments (`//`) and declarations mixed with code.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Some of the C99-introduced features were included in the subsequent version of the C++ standard, C++11 (out of those which were not redundant).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] However, the C++11 standard introduces new incompatibilities, such as disallowing assignment of a string literal to a character pointer, which remains valid C.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] To intermix C and C++ code, any function declaration or definition that is to be called from/used both in C and C++ must be declared with C linkage by placing it within an `extern "C" {/*...*/}` block.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Such a function may not rely on features depending on name mangling (i.e., function overloading).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Programs developed in C or C++ often utilize inline assembly to take advantage of its low-level functionalities, greater speed, and enhanced control compared to high-level programming languages when optimizing for performance is essential.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides support for embedding assembly language using asm declarations, but the compatibility of inline assembly varies significantly between compilers and architectures.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Unlike high-level language features such as Python or Java, assembly code is highly dependent on the underlying processor and compiler implementation.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] Different C++ compilers implement inline assembly in distinct ways.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides two primary methods of integrating ASM code: standalone assembly files, where assembly code is written separately and linked with C++ code.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/c] And inline assembly, where assembly code is embedded within C++ code using compiler-specific extensions.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generic programming was introduced to the mainstream with Ada in 1977.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] With templates in C++, generic programming became part of the repertoire of professional library design.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The techniques were further improved and *parameterized types* were introduced in the influential 1994 book *Design Patterns*.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] New techniques were introduced by Andrei Alexandrescu in his 2001 book *Modern C++ Design: Generic Programming and Design Patterns Applied*.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Subsequently, D implemented the same ideas.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Such software entities are known as *generics* in Ada, C#, Delphi, Eiffel, F#, Java, Mojo, Nim, Python, Go, Rust, Swift, TypeScript, and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] They are known as *parametric polymorphism* in ML, Scala, Julia, and Haskell.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The "generic programming" paradigm is an approach to software decomposition whereby fundamental requirements on types are abstracted from across concrete examples of algorithms and data structures and formalized as concepts, analogously to the abstraction of algebraic theories in abstract algebra.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Early examples of this programming approach were implemented in Scheme and Ada, although the best known example is the Standard Template Library (STL), which developed a theory of iterators that is used to decouple sequence data structures and the algorithms operating on them.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, given *N* sequence data structures, e.g. singly linked list, vector etc., and *M* algorithms to operate on them, e.g.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] `find`, `sort` etc., a direct approach would implement each algorithm specifically for each data structure, giving *N* × *M* combinations to implement.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Thus, only *N* + *M* data structure-algorithm combinations need be implemented.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] An important point is that a data structure will return a model of the most general concept that can be implemented efficiently—computational complexity requirements are explicitly part of the concept definition.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This limits the data structures a given algorithm can be applied to and such complexity requirements are a major determinant of data structure choice.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generic programming similarly has been applied in other domains, e.g. graph algorithms.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Although this approach often uses language features of compile-time genericity and templates, it is independent of particular language-technical details.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] — Alexander Stepanov, An Interview with A.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Other programming paradigms that have been described as generic programming include *Datatype generic programming* as described in "Generic Programming – an Introduction".
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The *Scrap your boilerplate* approach is a lightweight generic programming approach for Haskell.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In this article we distinguish the high-level programming paradigms of *generic programming*, above, from the lower-level programming language *genericity mechanisms* used to implement them (see Programming language support for genericity).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For further discussion and comparison of generic programming paradigms, see.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Genericity facilities have existed in high-level languages since at least the 1970s in languages such as ML, CLU and Ada, and were subsequently adopted by many object-based and object-oriented languages, including BETA, C++, D, Eiffel, Java, and DEC's now defunct Trellis-Owl.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Genericity is implemented and supported differently in various programming languages; the term "generic" has also been used differently in various programming contexts.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, in Forth the compiler can execute code while compiling and one can create new *compiler keywords* and new implementations for those words on the fly.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] It has few *words* that expose the compiler behaviour and therefore naturally offers *genericity* capacities that, however, are not referred to as such in most Forth texts.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The term has been used in functional programming, specifically in Haskell-like languages, which use a structural type system where types are always parametric and the actual code on those types is generic.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] These uses still serve a similar purpose of code-saving and rendering an abstraction.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Arrays and structs can be viewed as predefined generic types.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Every usage of an array or struct type instantiates a new concrete type, or reuses a previous instantiated type.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Array element types and struct element types are parameterized types, which are used to instantiate the corresponding generic type.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] All this is usually built-in in the compiler and the syntax differs from other generic constructs.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Some extensible programming languages try to unify built-in and user defined generic types.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A broad survey of genericity mechanisms in programming languages follows.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For a specific survey comparing suitability of mechanisms for generic programming, see.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] When creating container classes in statically typed languages, it is inconvenient to write specific implementations for each datatype contained, especially if the code for each datatype is virtually identical.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Above, `T` is a placeholder for whatever type is specified when the list is created.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] These "generic objects of type `T`", commonly called templates, allow a class to be reused with different datatypes as long as certain contracts such as subtypes and signature are kept.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This genericity mechanism should not be confused with *inclusion polymorphism*, which is the algorithmic usage of exchangeable sub-classes: for instance, a list of objects of type `MovingEntity` containing objects of type `Animal` and `Car`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The C++ `template` construct used above is widely cited as the genericity construct that popularized the notion among programmers and language designers and supports many generic programming idioms.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The D language also offers fully generic-capable templates based on the C++ precedent but with a simplified syntax.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The Java language has provided genericity facilities syntactically based on C++'s since the introduction of Java Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE) 5.0.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] C# 2.0, Oxygene 1.5 (formerly Chrome) and Visual Basic (.NET) 2005 have constructs that exploit the support for generics present in Microsoft .NET Framework since version 2.0.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Ada has had generics since it was first designed in 1977–1980.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The standard library uses generics to provide many services.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Ada 2005 adds a comprehensive generic container library to the standard library, which was inspired by C++'s Standard Template Library.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A *generic unit* is a package or a subprogram that takes one or more *generic formal parameters*.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A *generic formal parameter* is a value, a variable, a constant, a type, a subprogram, or even an instance of another, designated, generic unit.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For generic formal types, the syntax distinguishes between discrete, floating-point, fixed-point, access (pointer) types, etc.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Some formal parameters can have default values.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] To *instantiate* a generic unit, the programmer passes *actual* parameters for each formal.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The generic instance then behaves just like any other unit.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] It is possible to instantiate generic units at run-time, for example, inside a loop.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The language syntax allows precise specification of constraints on generic formal parameters.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, it is possible to specify that a generic formal type will only accept a modular type as the actual.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In this example, `Array_Type` is constrained by both `Index_Type` and `Element_Type`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] When instantiating the unit, the programmer must pass an actual array type that satisfies these constraints.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The disadvantage of this fine-grained control is a complicated syntax, but, because all generic formal parameters are completely defined in the specification, the compiler can instantiate generics without looking at the body of the generic.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Unlike C++, Ada does not allow specialised generic instances, and requires that all generics be instantiated explicitly.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] C++ uses templates to enable generic programming techniques.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The C++ Standard Library includes the Standard Template Library or STL that provides a framework of templates for common data structures and algorithms.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Templates in C++ may also be used for template metaprogramming, which is a way of pre-evaluating some of the code at compile-time rather than run-time.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Using template specialization, C++ Templates are Turing complete.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] There are many kinds of templates, the most common being function templates and class templates.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A *function template* is a pattern for creating ordinary functions based upon the parameterizing types supplied when instantiated.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, the C++ Standard Template Library contains the function template `std::max(x, y)` that creates functions that return either `x` or `y`, whichever is larger.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The compiler examines the arguments used to call `max` and determines that this is a call to `max(int, int)`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This works whether the arguments `x` and `y` are integers, strings, or any other type for which the expression `x < y` is sensible, or more specifically, for any type for which `operator<` is defined.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Common inheritance is not needed for the set of types that can be used, and so it is very similar to duck typing.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A program defining a custom data type can use operator overloading to define the meaning of `<` for that type, thus allowing its use with the `std::max()` function template.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] While this may seem a minor benefit in this isolated example, in the context of a comprehensive library like the STL it allows the programmer to get extensive functionality for a new data type, just by defining a few operators for it.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Merely defining `<` allows a type to be used with the standard `std::sort()`, `std::stable_sort()`, and `std::binary_search()` algorithms or to be put inside data structures such as `std::set<T>`s (equivalent to `TreeSet<T>`, heaps, and associative arrays.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] C++ templates are completely type safe at compile time.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] As a demonstration, the standard type `std::complex<T>` does not define the `<` operator, because there is no strict order on complex numbers.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Therefore, `std::max(x, y)` will fail with a compile error, if `x` and `y` are `complex` values.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Likewise, other templates that rely on `<` cannot be applied to `complex` data unless a comparison (in the form of a functor or function) is provided.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For instance, `std::complex<T>` cannot be used as key for a `std::map<K, V>` (equivalent to `TreeMap<K, V>`) unless a comparison is provided.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Unfortunately, compilers historically generate somewhat esoteric, long, and unhelpful error messages for this sort of error.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Ensuring that a certain object adheres to a method protocol can alleviate this issue.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Languages which use `std::compare` instead of `<` can also use `std::complex<T>` values as keys.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Another kind of template, a *class template*, extends the same concept to classes.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A class template specialization is a class.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Class templates are often used to make generic containers.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, the STL has a doubly linked list container, `std::list<T>` (equivalent to `LinkedList<T>`).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] To make a linked list of integers, one writes `list<int>`, while a list of strings is denoted `list<string>`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A `std::list<T>` has a set of standard functions associated with it, that work for any compatible parameterizing types.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] C++20 introduces constraining template types using concepts.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A powerful feature of C++'s templates is *template specialization*.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This allows alternative implementations to be provided based on certain characteristics of the parameterized type that is being instantiated.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Template specialization has two purposes: to allow certain forms of optimization, and to reduce code bloat.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, consider a `sort()` template function.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] One of the primary activities that such a function does is to swap or exchange the values in two of the container's positions.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] If the values are large (in terms of the number of bytes it takes to store each of them), then it is often quicker to first build a separate list of pointers to the objects, sort those pointers, and then build the final sorted sequence.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] If the values are quite small however it is usually fastest to just swap the values in-place as needed.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Furthermore, if the parameterized type is already of some pointer-type, then there is no need to build a separate pointer array.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Template specialization allows the template creator to write different implementations and to specify the characteristics that the parameterized type(s) must have for each implementation to be used.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Unlike function templates, class templates can be partially specialized.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] That means that an alternate version of the class template code can be provided when some of the template parameters are known, while leaving other template parameters generic.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This can be used, for example, to create a default implementation (the *primary specialization*) that assumes that copying a parameterizing type is expensive and then create partial specializations for types that are cheap to copy, thus increasing overall efficiency.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Clients of such a class template just use specializations of it without needing to know whether the compiler used the primary specialization or some partial specialization in each case.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Class templates can also be *fully specialized,* which means that an alternate implementation can be provided when all of the parameterizing types are known.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Some uses of templates, such as the `max()` function, were formerly filled by function-like preprocessor macros (a legacy of the C language).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Macros are expanded (copy pasted) by the preprocessor, before program compiling; templates are actual real functions.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Macros are always expanded inline; templates can also be inline functions when the compiler deems it appropriate.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] However, templates are generally considered an improvement over macros for these purposes.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Templates avoid some of the common errors found in code that makes heavy use of function-like macros, such as evaluating parameters with side effects twice.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Perhaps most importantly, templates were designed to be applicable to much larger problems than macros.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Many compilers historically had poor support for templates, thus the use of templates could make code somewhat less portable.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Support may also be poor when a C++ compiler is being used with a linker that is not C++-aware, or when attempting to use templates across shared library boundaries.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Compilers can produce confusing, long, and sometimes unhelpful error messages when errors are detected in code that uses SFINAE.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This can make templates difficult to develop with.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Finally, the use of templates requires the compiler to generate a separate *instance* of the templated class or function for every type parameters used with it.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] (This is necessary because types in C++ are not all the same size, and the sizes of data fields are important to how classes work.) So the indiscriminate use of templates can lead to code bloat, resulting in excessively large executables.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] However, judicious use of template specialization and derivation can dramatically reduce such code bloat in some cases:So, can derivation be used to reduce the problem of code replicated because templates are used?
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This would involve deriving a template from an ordinary class.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This technique proved successful in curbing code bloat in real use.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Templated classes or functions may require an *explicit specialization* of the template class which would require rewriting of an entire class for a specific template parameters used by it.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The extra instantiations generated by templates can also cause some debuggers to have difficulty working gracefully with templates.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, setting a debug breakpoint within a template from a source file may either miss setting the breakpoint in the actual instantiation desired or may set a breakpoint in every place the template is instantiated.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Also, the implementation source code for the template must be completely available (e.g. included in a header) to the translation unit (source file) using it.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Templates, including much of the Standard Library, if not included in header files, cannot be compiled.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] (This is in contrast to non-templated code, which may be compiled to binary, providing only a declarations header file for code using it.) This may be a disadvantage by exposing the implementing code, which removes some abstractions, and could restrict its use in closed-source projects.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The D language supports templates based in design on C++.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Templates in D use a different syntax than in C++: whereas in C++ template parameters are wrapped in angular brackets (`Template<param1, param2>`), D uses an exclamation sign and parentheses: `Template!(param1, param2)`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This avoids the C++ parsing difficulties due to ambiguity with comparison operators.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] If there is only one parameter, the parentheses can be omitted.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Conventionally, D combines the above features to provide compile-time polymorphism using trait-based generic programming.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Combining the above allows generating code based on existing declarations.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, D serialization frameworks can enumerate a type's members and generate specialized functions for each serialized type to perform serialization and deserialization.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] User-defined attributes could further indicate serialization rules.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The `import` expression and compile-time function execution also allow efficiently implementing domain-specific languages.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generic classes have been a part of Eiffel since the original method and language design.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The foundation publications of Eiffel, use the term *genericity* to describe creating and using generic classes.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generic classes are declared with their class name and a list of one or more *formal generic parameters*.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The formal generic parameters are placeholders for arbitrary class names that will be supplied when a declaration of the generic class is made, as shown in the two *generic derivations* below, where `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are other class names.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are considered *actual generic parameters* as they provide real class names to substitute for `G` in actual use.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Within the Eiffel type system, although class `LIST [G]` is considered a class, it is not considered a type.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] However, a generic derivation of `LIST [G]` such as `LIST [ACCOUNT]` is considered a type.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For the list class shown above, an actual generic parameter substituting for `G` can be any other available class.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] To constrain the set of classes from which valid actual generic parameters can be chosen, a *generic constraint* can be specified.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In the declaration of class `SORTED_LIST` below, the generic constraint dictates that any valid actual generic parameter will be a class that inherits from class `COMPARABLE`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The generic constraint ensures that elements of a `SORTED_LIST` can in fact be sorted.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Support for the *generics*, or "containers-of-type-T" was added to the Java programming language in 2004 as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In Java, generics are only checked at compile time for type correctness.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The generic type information is then removed via a process called type erasure, to maintain compatibility with old JVM implementations, making it unavailable at runtime.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For example, a `List<String>` is converted to the raw type `java.util.List`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The compiler inserts type casts to convert the elements to the `java.lang.String` type when they are retrieved from the list, reducing performance compared to other implementations such as C++ templates.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generics were added as part of .NET Framework 2.0 in November 2005, based on a research prototype from Microsoft Research started in 1999.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Although similar to generics in Java, .NET generics do not apply type erasure, but implement generics as a first class mechanism in the runtime using reification.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This design choice provides additional functionality, such as allowing reflection with preservation of generic types, and alleviating some of the limits of erasure (such as being unable to create generic arrays).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This also means that there is no performance hit from runtime casts and normally expensive boxing conversions.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] When primitive and value types are used as generic arguments, they get specialized implementations, allowing for efficient generic collections and methods.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] As in C++ and Java, nested generic types such as `Dictionary<string, List<int>>` are valid types, however are advised against for member signatures in code analysis design rules.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] .NET allows six varieties of generic type constraints using the `where` keyword including restricting generic types to be value types, to be classes, to have constructors, and to implement interfaces.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The `MakeAtLeast()` method allows operation on arrays, with elements of generic type `T`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The method's type constraint indicates that the method is applicable to any type `T` that implements the generic `System.IComparable<T>` interface.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This ensures a compile time error, if the method is called if the type does not support comparison.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The interface provides the generic method `CompareTo(T)`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The above method could also be written without generic types, simply using the non-generic `System.Array` type.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] However, since arrays are contravariant, the casting would not be type safe, and the compiler would be unable to find certain possible errors that would otherwise be caught when using generic types.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In addition, the method would need to access the array items as `object`s instead, and would require casting to compare two elements.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A notable behavior of static members in a generic .NET class is static member instantiation per run-time type (see example below).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] For Pascal, generics were first implemented in 2006, in the implementation Free Pascal.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The Object Pascal dialect Delphi acquired generics in the 2007 Delphi 11 release by CodeGear, initially only with the .NET compiler (since discontinued) before being added to the native code in the 2009 Delphi 12 release.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The semantics and abilities of Delphi generics are largely modelled on those of generics in .NET 2.0, though the implementation is by necessity quite different.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] As with C#, methods and whole types can have one or more type parameters.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In the example, TArray is a generic type (defined by the language) and MakeAtLeast a generic method.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The available constraints are very similar to the available constraints in C#: any value type, any class, a specific class or interface, and a class with a parameterless constructor.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Multiple constraints act as an additive union.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Free Pascal implemented generics in 2006 in version 2.2.0, before Delphi and with different syntax and semantics.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] However, since FPC version 2.6.0, the Delphi-style syntax is available when using the language mode `{$mode Delphi}`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Thus, Free Pascal code supports generics in either style.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The type class mechanism of Haskell supports generic programming.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] All the necessary methods will be "derived" – that is, constructed automatically – based on the structure of the type.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] This results in an equality function (`==`) and a string representation function (`show`) being automatically defined for any type of the form `BinTree T` provided that `T` itself supports those operations.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Ralf Hinze (2004) has shown that a similar effect can be achieved for user-defined type classes by certain programming techniques.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Other researchers have proposed approaches to this and other kinds of genericity in the context of Haskell and extensions to Haskell (discussed below).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] PolyP was the first generic programming language extension to Haskell.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] In PolyP, generic functions are called *polytypic*.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The language introduces a special construct in which such polytypic functions can be defined via structural induction over the structure of the pattern functor of a regular datatype.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Regular datatypes in PolyP are a subset of Haskell datatypes.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A regular datatype t must be of kind ** → **, and if *a* is the formal type argument in the definition, then all recursive calls to *t* must have the form *t a*.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] These restrictions rule out higher-kinded datatypes and nested datatypes, where the recursive calls are of a different form.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generic Haskell is another extension to Haskell, developed at Utrecht University in the Netherlands.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] The resulting type-indexed value can be specialized to any type.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Clean offers generic programming based PolyP and the Generic Haskell as supported by the GHC ≥ 6.0.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] It parametrizes by kind as those but offers overloading.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Languages in the ML family support generic programming through parametric polymorphism and generic modules called *functors.* Both Standard ML and OCaml provide functors, which are similar to class templates and to Ada's generic packages.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Scheme syntactic abstractions also have a connection to genericity – these are in fact a superset of C++ templates.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] A Verilog module may take one or more parameters, to which their actual values are assigned upon the instantiation of the module.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] One example is a generic register array where the array width is given via a parameter.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Such an array, combined with a generic wire vector, can make a generic buffer or memory module with an arbitrary bit width out of a single module implementation.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] VHDL, being derived from Ada, also has generic abilities.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] C has a feature called "type-generic expressions" using the `_Generic` keyword: This feature gives C function overloading capabilities, but is not related to generic programming.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Generic programming can be achieved by using the preprocessor to define the generic code, with macro expansion taking the role of *instantiation*.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/generic-programming] Sometimes, the non-standard extension "statement expressions" is used to simulate function-like behaviour for generic code.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] In computer science, a **smart pointer** is an abstract data type that simulates a pointer while providing added features, such as automatic memory management or bounds checking.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Such features are intended to reduce bugs caused by the misuse of pointers, while retaining efficiency.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Smart pointers typically keep track of the memory they point to, and may also be used to manage other resources, such as network connections and file handles.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Smart pointers were first popularized in the programming language C++ during the first half of the 1990s as rebuttal to criticisms of C++'s lack of automatic garbage collection.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Rust, which avoids raw pointers and uses ownership to dictate lifetimes, also has smart pointers.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Pointer misuse can be a major source of bugs.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Smart pointers prevent most situations of memory leaks by making the memory deallocation automatic.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Smart pointers also eliminate dangling pointers by postponing destruction until an object is no longer in use.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Java, although not having a pointer API, has similar concepts for dealing with references.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Some work with reference counting, others by assigning ownership of an object to one pointer.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Even though C++ popularized the concept of smart pointers, especially the reference-counted variety, the immediate predecessor of one of the languages that inspired C++'s design had reference-counted references built into the language.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Insofar as Simula I's *element* is analogous to C++'s pointer without *null*, and insofar as Simula I's process with a dummy-statement as its activity body is analogous to C++'s *struct* (which itself is analogous to C.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Hoare's *record* in then-contemporary 1960s work), Simula I had reference counted elements (i.e., pointer-expressions that house indirection) to processes (i.e., records) no later than September 1965, as shown in the quoted paragraphs below.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Because C++ borrowed Simula's approach to memory allocation—the *new* keyword when allocating a process/record to obtain a fresh *element* to that process/record—it is not surprising that C++ eventually resurrected Simula's reference-counted smart-pointer mechanism within *element* as well.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] In C++, a smart pointer is implemented as a template class that mimics, by means of operator overloading, the behaviors of a traditional (raw) pointer, (e.g. dereferencing, assignment) while providing additional memory management features.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Smart pointers can facilitate intentional programming by expressing, in the type, how the memory of the referent of the pointer will be managed.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] For example, if a C++ function returns a pointer, there is no way to know whether the caller should delete the memory of the referent when the caller is finished with the information.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Traditionally, naming conventions have been used to resolve the ambiguity, which is an error-prone, labor-intensive approach.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] The declaration of the function return type as a `unique_ptr` makes explicit the fact that the caller takes ownership of the result, and the C++ runtime ensures that the memory will be reclaimed automatically.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Before C++11, `unique_ptr` can be replaced with auto_ptr, which is now deprecated.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] It is preferred, in almost all circumstances, to use these facilities over the `new` keyword.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] C++11 introduces `std::unique_ptr`, defined in the header `<memory>`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] A `unique_ptr` is a container for a raw pointer, which the `unique_ptr` is said to own.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] A `unique_ptr` explicitly prevents copying of its contained pointer (as would happen with normal assignment), but the `std::move` function can be used to transfer ownership of the contained pointer to another `unique_ptr`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] A `unique_ptr` cannot be copied because its copy constructor and assignment operators are explicitly deleted.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] `std::auto_ptr` is deprecated under C++11 and completely removed from C++17.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] The copy constructor and assignment operators of `auto_ptr` do not actually copy the stored pointer.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Instead, they transfer it, leaving the prior `auto_ptr` object empty.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] This was one way to implement strict ownership, so that only one `auto_ptr` object can own the pointer at any given time.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] This means that `auto_ptr` should not be used where copy semantics are needed.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Since `auto_ptr` already existed with its copy semantics, it could not be upgraded to be a move-only pointer without breaking backward compatibility with existing code.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] The Rust equivalent of unique pointers is `std::boxed::Box`, which has unique ownership of a heap allocated object.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] In previous versions of Rust, there was also a `std::ptr::Unique` that wrapped around raw non-null `*mut T`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] It is possible to use "smart void pointers" using `std::unique_ptr`, using its second template parameter `Deleter`, which stores a type of a deallocator.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] C++11 introduces `std::shared_ptr` and `std::weak_ptr`, defined in the header `<memory>`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] C++11 also introduces `std::make_shared` (`std::make_unique` was introduced in C++14) to safely allocate dynamic memory in the RAII paradigm.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] A `shared_ptr` is a container for a raw pointer.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] It maintains reference counting ownership of its contained pointer in cooperation with all copies of the `shared_ptr`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] An object referenced by the contained raw pointer will be destroyed when and only when all copies of the `shared_ptr` have been destroyed.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] A `weak_ptr` is a container for a raw pointer.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] It is created as a copy of a `shared_ptr`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] The existence or destruction of `weak_ptr` copies of a `shared_ptr` have no effect on the `shared_ptr` or its other copies.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] After all copies of a `shared_ptr` have been destroyed, all `weak_ptr` copies become empty.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Because the implementation of `shared_ptr` uses reference counting, circular references are potentially a problem.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] A circular `shared_ptr` chain can be broken by changing the code so that one of the references is a `weak_ptr`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Multiple threads can safely simultaneously access different `shared_ptr` and `weak_ptr` objects that point to the same object.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] The referenced object must be protected separately to ensure thread safety.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] `shared_ptr` and `weak_ptr` are based on versions used by the Boost libraries.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] C++ Technical Report 1 (TR1) first introduced them to the standard, as general utilities, but C++11 adds more functions, in line with the Boost version.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] In Java, every object is effectively a shared reference, and the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) tracks object reachability.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Rust has two kinds of shared pointers, `std::rc::Rc` (reference-counted, single-threaded) and `std::sync::Arc` (atomically reference-counted, thread-safe).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Java has an equivalent concept to weak pointers, `java.lang.ref.WeakReference` (implementing a weak reference), which does not increase the reference count of an object, and can check that an object still lives using `WeakReference::get`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Java similarly has the `java.lang.ref.PhantomReference` (implementing a phantom reference), used with a `java.lang.ref.ReferenceQueue`, for performing cleanup actions after an object is garbage collected, but prior to finalisation.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Unlike `WeakReference`), `PhantomReference` cannot actually access the object.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] `java.lang.ref.SoftReference`, on the other hand, are cleared according to the discretion of the garbage collector.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Rust has a `std::rc::Weak` for a weak, non-owning reference which is created from an `Rc` or `Arc` by using `downgrade()`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] Starting in C++26, there is a new pointer defined in `<hazard_pointer>`, the hazard pointer (`std::hazard_pointer`).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] It is a single-writer multi-reader pointer that can be owned by at most one thread at any point in time.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] The hazard pointer had existed already previously in some third-party libraries.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/smart-pointer] There are other types of smart pointers (which are not in the C++ standard) implemented on popular C++ libraries or custom STL, some examples include the intrusive pointer.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] In plain terms, a templated class or function would be the equivalent of (before "compiling") copying and pasting the templated block of code where it is used, and then replacing the template parameter with the actual one.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] For this reason, classes employing templated methods place the implementation in the headers (*.h files) as no symbol could be compiled without knowing the type beforehand.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] The C++ Standard Library provides many useful functions within a framework of connected templates.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Major inspirations for C++ templates were the parameterized modules provided by the language CLU and the generics provided by Ada.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] There are three kinds of templates: *function templates*, *class templates* and, since C++14, *variable templates*.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Since C++11, templates may be either variadic or non-variadic; in earlier versions of C++ they are always non-variadic.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] A *function template* behaves like a function except that the template can accept arguments of various types, enabling type-generic behavior (see example).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] In other words, a function template represents a family of functions.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Both expressions have the same meaning and behave in exactly the same way.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] The latter form was introduced to avoid confusion, since a type parameter need not be a class until C++20.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] For example, the C++ Standard Library contains the function template `max(x, y)` which returns the larger of `x` and `y`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] This single function definition works with many data types.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Specifically, it works with all data types for which **<** (the less-than operator) is defined and returns a value with a type convertible to `bool`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] The usage of a function template saves space in the source code file in addition to limiting changes to one function description and making the code easier to read.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] An instantiated function template usually produces the same object code, though, compared to writing separate functions for all the different data types used in a specific program.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] For example, if a program uses both an `int` and a `double` version of the `max()` function template above, the compiler will create an object code version of `max()` that operates on `int` arguments and another object code version that operates on `double` arguments.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] The compiler output will be identical to what would have been produced if the source code had contained two separate non-templated versions of `max()`, one written to handle `int` and one written to handle `double`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] In the first two cases, the template argument `T` is automatically deduced by the compiler to be `int` and `double`, respectively.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] In the third case automatic deduction of `max(3, 7.0)` would fail because the type of the parameters must in general match the template arguments exactly.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Therefore, we explicitly instantiate the `double` version with `max<double>()`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] This function template can be instantiated with any copy-constructible type for which the expression `y < x` is valid.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] For user-defined types, this implies that the less-than operator (`<`) must be overloaded in the type.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Since C++20, using `auto` or `concept auto` in any of the parameters of a function declaration, that declaration becomes an *abbreviated function template* declaration.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] A class template provides a specification for generating classes based on parameters.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Class templates are generally used to implement containers.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] A class template is instantiated by passing a given set of types to it as template arguments.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] The C++ Standard Library contains many class templates, in particular the containers adapted from the Standard Template Library, such as `vector`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Although templating on types, as in the examples above, is the most common form of templating in C++, it is also possible to template on values.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] can be instantiated with a specific `int`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] As a real-world example, the standard library fixed-size array type `std::array` is templated on both a type (representing the type of object that the array holds) and a number which is of type `std::size_t` (representing the number of elements the array holds).
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] When a function or class is instantiated from a template, a specialization of that template is created by the compiler for the set of arguments used, and the specialization is referred to as being a generated specialization.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Sometimes, the programmer may decide to implement a special version of a function (or class) for a given set of template type arguments which is called an explicit specialization.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] In this way certain template types can have a specialized implementation that is optimized for the type or a more meaningful implementation than the generic implementation.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Explicit specialization is used when the behavior of a function or class for particular choices of the template parameters must deviate from the generic behavior: that is, from the code generated by the main template, or templates.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] C++11 introduced variadic templates, which can take a variable number of arguments in a manner somewhat similar to variadic functions such as `std::printf`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Because only C-style variadic parameters are supported in C++, the only way to get type-safe variadic functions (like in Java) is through variadic templates.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] C++11 introduced template aliases, which act like parameterized typedefs.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] The following code shows renaming `std::map` to `TreeMap` and `std::unordered_map` to `HashMap`, as well as creating an alias `StringHashMap` for `std::unordered_map<K, std::string>`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] This allows, for example, `StringHashMap<int>` to be used as shorthand for `std::unordered_map<int, std::string>`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Since C++20, templates can be constrained similarly to generics wildcards in Java or C# and Rust `where` clauses.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] This is done using concepts, which represent a set of boolean predicates evaluated at compile time.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] For example, this code uses `std::derived_from<Derived, Based>` as an upper inheritance bound.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] A class satisfies this concept if it inherits from `Player`, and classes that do not cannot be used as the template parameter in `processListOfPlayers()`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Concepts can be used to implement a form of type-safe variadic parameters.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Furthermore, to constrain these to any specific type, the `std::same_as<T, U>` and `std::convertible_to<T, U>` concepts may be used.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] For instance, the Java signatures `void foo(int... args);` and `void bar(String... args);` could be written as `void foo(same_as<int> auto... args);` and `void bar(convertible_to<string> auto... args);` respectively.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] In C++03, "exported templates" were added to C++.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] These were later removed in C++11, due to very few compilers actually supporting the feature.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] The only compiler known to support exported templates was Comeau C/C++.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] An "exported template" is essentially a class template whose static data members and non-inline methods are exported.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] It must be marked by the keyword `export`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] What distinguishes an "exported template" is the fact that it does not need to be defined in a translation unit that uses the template.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] With the introduction of modules in C++20, the keyword `export` was re-added to C++.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] The compilation speed benefits intended to be offered by exported templates are offered by modules anyway, making the feature essentially obsolete and superseded by modules.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Initially, the concept of templates was not included in some languages, such as Java and C# 1.0.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Java's adoption of generics mimics the behavior of templates, but is technically different.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] C# added generics (parameterized types) in .NET 2.0.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] The generics in Ada predate C++ templates.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Although C++ templates, Java generics, and .NET generics are often considered similar, generics only mimic the basic behavior of C++ templates.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] In C++ templates, compile-time cases were historically performed by pattern matching over the template arguments.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] For example, the template base class in the Factorial example below is implemented by matching 0 rather than with an inequality test, which was previously unavailable.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] However, the arrival in C++11 of standard library features such as `std::conditional` has provided another, more flexible way to handle conditional template instantiation.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] With these definitions, one can compute, say 6! at compile time using the expression `Factorial<6>::value`.
[src:boost-cpp-lib/template-c] Because of this, template meta-programming is now mostly used to do operations on types.
